==German==
===Etymology===
Originally a term to make fun of students from the vicinity of [[Halle]], Germany in the 18th century. This part of the country was famous for cultivating caraway ([[Kümmel]]) and was thus termed ''Kümmeltürkei''. In modern times, only used as a derogative term for foreigners of middle eastern and Turkish descent, from the notion that Turkish people supposedly smell like [[caraway]] (ironically, caraway is much more frequent in German than in Turkish cooking); also onomatopoetically because of the high frequency of the umlaut "ü" in the Turkish language, e.g. in ''güle güle'' - "goodbye".<br>It should also be mentioned that the founder of modern Turkey was ''Kemal Atatürk'', which sounds similar. Compare [[Kümmelblättchen]], in which the ''Kümmel-'' is derived from Hebrew ''gimel'', "three".

===Noun===
'''Kümmeltürke''' ''m''
# very derogative and xenophobic term for a [[turkish]] or Middle Eastern person.
